Part 1: Basics of Image Motion¶

A ball thrown in the air follows a parabolic trajectory under the effect of gravity. Atmospheric effects are negligible. As a result, the horizontal velocity of the ball is constant and its vertical motion undergoes constant acceleration downwards. The ball is filmed by a static black-and-white camera which sees the whole trajectory from the side (that is, the image plane of the camera is parallel to the plane that contains the trajectory). The ball translates and does not spin. As a consequence, its image moves by a pure translation in the image plane. That is, all points visible on the ball move by the same image motion.

The center of the ball is at position $\mathbf{x}(t)$ in the image at time $t$. The components $x(t)$ and $y(t)$ of $\mathbf{x}(t)$ are measured in pixels relative to the initial position of the ball in the image when recording is started at time $t=0$. Specifically, $x(t)$ is measured horizontally (increasing left-to-right) and $y(t)$ vertically (increasing top-down).

The components of $\mathbf{x}(t)$ are found to be

$$ \begin{eqnarray*} x(t) &=& a t \\ y(t) &=& b t + c t^2 \end{eqnarray*} $$

where

$$ \begin{eqnarray*} \mathbf{a} &=& (a, b) = (10, -20)\; \mbox{pixels per frame}\\ c &=& 12\; \mbox{pixels per frame squared.} \end{eqnarray*} $$

Problem 1.1 (Exam Style)¶

What is the image motion field $\mathbf{u}(t)$ at image position $\mathbf{x}(t)$ at time $t$, measured in pixels per frame? Give both formulas for the two components $u(t)$ and $v(t)$ of $\mathbf{u}(t)$ in terms of $a, b, c, t$ and their numerical values for $t = 0$ frames and for $t = 1$ frame. Include units of measure for your numerical answers.

Problem 1.2 (Exam Style)¶

The image brightness pattern $e(\mathbf{x}, t)$ on the ball is found to have a spatial gradient $\nabla e$ at the center $\mathbf{x}(t)$ of the ball. This gradient is unchanged over time and the numerical values of its components are

$$ \begin{eqnarray*} e_x &=& \frac{\partial e}{\partial x} = 3\; \text{gray levels per pixel} \\ e_y &=& \frac{\partial e}{\partial y} = 4\; \text{gray levels per pixel.} \end{eqnarray*} $$

A "gray level" is whatever unit brightness is measured in. For instance, you could think of it as a real number between 0 and 1, or between 0 and 255.

Write a formula in terms of $a, b, c, t, e_x, e_y$ for the normal component $\omega(t)$ of the motion field at position $\mathbf{x}(t)$ and time $t$. Then give the value of $\omega(0)$. Include the unit of measure for your numerical answer.

Note¶

  • By its definition, the normal component of the motion field is a signed scalar.

Then give the numerical value of this partial derivative at time $t=0$. Include the unit of measure for your numerical answer.

import urllib.request
import ssl
from os import path as osp
import shutil


def retrieve(file_name, semester='spring24', homework=3):
    if osp.exists(file_name):
        print('Using previously downloaded file {}'.format(file_name))
    else:
        context = ssl._create_unverified_context()
        fmt = 'https://www2.cs.duke.edu/courses/{}/compsci527/homework/{}/{}'
        url = fmt.format(semester, homework, file_name)
        with urllib.request.urlopen(url, context=context) as response:
            with open(file_name, 'wb') as file:
                shutil.copyfileobj(response, file)
        print('Downloaded file {}'.format(file_name))

What happened here is a luxury we do not have in the real world. First, the world is synthetic: An object that looks a bit like a bolt or a hat is placed in the middle of a cylindrical room. Most surfaces have a smooth texture on them, and everything is designed so that appearance is exactly constant as the virtual camera moves around. This type of simulation is not unusual, as this is what computer graphics does all the time.

More importantly, however, everything is known analytically, including the shapes of all surfaces and all surface texture patterns. In contrast, computer graphics wuold represent shapes with a point cloud and a triangular mesh, and then shade the triangles with some shading algorithm. Look at ideal.py if you want to see how an analytic world can be made.

Because of this, we can think of perspective projection (the process by which a camera creates images of the world) as a function $e(x, y, t)$ where $x, y$ are image coordinates, $t$ is time, and $e$ is image brightness. Variable $x$ goes left to right and variable $y$ goes top-bottom, and the origin is the upper-left corner of the image.

We can then use autograd to differentiate the function $e(x, y, t)$ exactly (to within machine precision; this caveat is henceforth implied). This has two advantages:

  • We can compute images at arbitrary resolution both in space ($x, y$) and time ($t$).
  • We get exact values for the spatial gradient $\nabla e$ and the partial time derivative $e_t$, again at arbitrary resolution.

Obviously you cannot do this with a real camera. This ideal, artificial setup lets you compare motion estimates with the ground truth and work in an environment where everything is tightly under control.

Specifically, in the code provided, the virtual camera rotates on a circle around the virtual object. The circle is in a tilted plane, so from the object's point of view the camera looks like the sun that rises and sets. The camera always points toward the centroid of the object, so the object remains in the field of view.

We can then use automatic differentiation (autograd, discussed in a previous assignment) to compute the true motion field: Start with image point coordinates $\mathbf{p}$ in image_0, trace the projection ray of $\mathbf{p}$ outwards in space to see where it intersects a surface in the world to find the world point $\mathbf{P}$ that projects to $\mathbf{p}$, and then invert the process to compute image coordinates $x, y = \pi(\mathbf{P}, t)$, where $\pi$ is the perspective projection function.

Of course you get $\mathbf{p}$ back with this process. However, we can now use autograd again by keeping the world points $\mathbf{P}$ fixed and compute the derivatives of the image $x, y$ corodinates for each point as a function of $t$ as the camera moves. These derivatives are the exact true motion field:

In [6]:
u = motion_field(frame_number_0, camera, world)
In [7]:
field_image = show_field(u)
stats(np.linalg.norm(u, axis=2), 'motion field magnitude in pixels per frame')

Statistics of the motion field magnitude in pixels per frame:
minimum: 0.009181, maximum: 1.234, mean absolute value: 0.6478, standard deviation: 0.252

Cool, no? This visualization of the motion field is standard in the literature: The hue (orange versus green or red or yellow) encodes direction of the field in $[0, 2\pi)$ and saturation (how far the color is from white) encodes the magnitude. We would need to know the exact encoding to interpret the colors, but this plot is here just to show that the field is smooth and that the background moves differently from the foreground.

Problem 2.1 (Exam Style, Except for the Code)¶

This problem presents a puzzle that you are asked to explain.

The sampling grid (location of the pixel centers) in frame 0 can be retrieved as follows:

In [12]:
grid_0 = camera.image_grid()

This is a $301\times 301\times 2$ array with the $x$ (grid_0[:, :, 0]) and $y$ (grid_0[:, :, 1]) coordinates of each pixel in the image. The displacement field d computed earlier gives the motion between frame 0 and frame 1 for every pixel position in frame 0, and therefore the new point positions in frame 1 are computed as follows:

In [13]:
grid_1 = grid_0 + d

Suppose now that we take the points in grid_1 and we determine their displacements back to frame 0. This can be done with the optional parameter grid in the function displacement:

In [14]:
d_back = displacement(frame_number_1, frame_number_0, camera, world, grid=grid_1)

Note the reverse order for the first two arguments: We are computing displacements going back in time.

We can now recompute the original grid:

In [15]:
grid_back = grid_1 + d_back

You could reasonably expect that grid_back and grid_0 are effectively the same grid, since we track points forward in time (using their true displacements, so no errors here!) and then back in time again (ditto).

However, if we plot the end-point error field between these two grids we obtain the following:

In [16]:
fb_epe = grid_back - grid_0
fb_epe_image = show_field(fb_epe)

Explain clearly which points are painted orange in the plot above. Try to explain what happened to the extent that you can.

Hint¶

The function displacement works as follows to compute the motion for each image point $\mathbf{p}$ in frame 0:

  • It figures out what point $\mathbf{P}$ in the world image point $\mathbf{p}$ corresponds to. That is, $\mathbf{p}$ is the projection of $\mathbf{P}$, as computed from the laws of perspective projection, and as if $\mathbf{P}$ were the only point in the world.
  • It moves the world point $\mathbf{P}$ by accounting for the true relative motion between camera and $\mathbf{P}$ between frame 0 and frame 1, to find a new world point $\mathbf{Q}$.
  • It projects the world point $\mathbf{Q}$ back to the image to find the point $\mathbf{q}$ in frame 1 that corresponds to point $\mathbf{p}$ in frame 0. Again this is done via the laws of perspective projection, and as if $\mathbf{Q}$ were the only point in the world.
  • It returns the displacement vector $\mathbf{d} = \mathbf{q} - \mathbf{p}$.

The gaussian window size is the size of the kernel used for differentiation. The feature window size is the size of the tracking window. The other two LK parameters are used to determine convergence.

Each point in points_and_window_sizes comes with a window size, currently set to 11 for all points. This value determines the feature window size for that point before it is tracked.

Part 4: Good Features to Track¶

Knowing that the Lucas-Kanade tracker is used for tracking points between two video frames yields a principled way to determine points in the first frame that can be tracked well, even without knowing what the second frame looks like. Points that can be tracked well are minimally affected by the aperture problem. The general idea is as follows:

  • Lucas-Kanade uses Newton-Raphson to track a point centered at $\mathbf{x}_f$ in frame $f$ (the first of two frames $f$, $f'$). This optimization technique is used to minimize the Sum of Squared Differences (SSD) between pairs of windows, one in $f$ and the other in $f'$, as a function of the displacement $\mathbf{d}$ between the two windows.
  • The basic iteration of Newton-Raphson solves a $2\times 2$ linear system $A(\mathbf{x}_{f'})\mathbf{d} = \mathbf{b}$ where the matrix $A(\mathbf{x}_{f'})$ is computed on a shifted version of $f'$.
  • Once the correct displacement is found, a window in the shifted frame $f'$ will look very similar to the corresponding window in frame $f$, since the shift is computed so that the two windows correspond.
  • So we can compute $A(\mathbf{x}_f)$ for all pixel positions $\mathbf{x}_f$ in $f$, rather than in $f'$. We don't even need to know $f'$ to do this. With small motions, the matrices $A(\mathbf{x}_{f'})$ encountered in Newton-Raphson are likely quite similar to each other and to $A(\mathbf{x}_{f})$.
  • The idea for finding good features is that Newton-Raphson will work reliably if the matrix $A(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is well-conditioned, so that the linear systems that Newton-Raphson needs to solve have unique solutions. A matrix is well-conditioned if its smaller eigenvalue is not too small (that is, the matrix is far from rank 1). Thus, pixels $\mathbf{x}_f$ for which the smaller eigenvalue of the matrix $A(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is large are good features to track.
  • The expression for $A(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is as follows, where $W(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is a square window of shape $(2h+1, 2h+1)$ pixels centered at $\mathbf{x}_f$, and where $\mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x}) = \nabla f(\mathbf{x})$ is the gradient of $f$ at $\mathbf{x}$. To keep things simple, no weight function is used.

$$ A(\mathbf{x}_f) = \sum_{\mathbf{x}\in W(\mathbf{x}_f)} \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x}) \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x})^T \;. $$

  • A window $W(\mathbf{x}_f)$ centered at $\mathbf{x}_f$ is a good feature to track if the following conditions are met:

    1. Feature quality: The smaller eigenvalue of $A(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is above some given positive threshold $\tau$.
    2. Sparse feature distribution: If a good feature exists at $\mathbf{x}_f$, no other good feature is chosen within some given minimum Euclidean distance $d_{\min}$ pixels from $\mathbf{x}_f$.
    3. Efficiency: There are at most $n_{\max}$ good features in $f$, where $n_{\max}$ is a given integer.

  • Of course, $\mathbf{x}_f$ cannot be too close to the image boundaries, or else $W(\mathbf{x}_f)$ will exceed the boundaries.

Programming Notes¶

For full credit, your code must comply with the following notes:

  • Compute the image gradient by convolving with Gaussians and their derivatives as shown in the class notes and using separability. For a Gaussian with parameter $\sigma$, make the kernel half-length $h_{\sigma} = \text{round}(3.5\sigma)$ so that the kernel length is $\ell = 2 h_{\sigma} + 1$ (for both differentiator and smoother). Use 'valid' convolutions (so the gradient is smaller than the input image). Use the function scipy.signal.convolve2d.
  • Use no for loops on image pixels in your code, or else your code would be hopelessly slow. To this end, note that the matrix $A$ is $2\times 2$ and symmetric, so it has three distinct entries. Let us call those $a_{11}, a_{12}, a_{22}$. Then $a_{21}$ is the same as $a_{12}$, so it does not need to be computed. To compute, say, $a_{12} = \sum_{\mathbf{x}\in W(\mathbf{x}_f)} g_1(\mathbf{x}) g_2(\mathbf{x})$ use a numpy array operation to compute the product $g_1g_2$ everywhere. Then, use the fact that the summation is a separable convolution. This is the case for any summation of the form $\sum_{\mathbf{x}\in W(\mathbf{x}_f)} p(\mathbf{x})$ where $W(\mathbf{x}_f)$ is a window. The fact that $p$ is a product is irrelevant. (You may have to think a bit to see how that is a convolution, and why it is separable.) Use 'valid' convolutions (so the resulting arrays are smaller than the gradient arrays).
  • Once you have $a_{11}, a_{12}, a_{22}$ everywhere (as three numpy arrays or, if you prefer, as a single $r\times c\times 3$ array), you can compute eigenvalues using the closed-form formula for eigenvalues of a symmetric $2\times 2$ matrix. Feel free to look that up.
  • Since both eigenvalues need to be at least $\tau$, all you need to compute is the smaller of the two (the one with the minus sign!). The smaller eigenvalue can be computed everywhere all at once with numpy array operations using the formula.
  • Make row, column indices for all the image entries corresponding to the eigenvalue entries. The indices refer to the full image, but the eigenvalue array is only part of it because of the 'valid' convolutions. You may want to make a helper function to compute these indices.
  • Now you have the row, column locations and corresponding eigenvalues for all the window centers $\mathbf{x}_f$ with sufficiently large eigenvalues (condition 1). To satisfy conditions 2 and 3, sort the pixels in order of decreasing eigenvalue (as you sort eigenvalues, reorder the corresponding row, column indices as well). Put the item that is at the top of the sorted list in the final set of good features. Remove all points in the list that are closer than $d_{\min}$ to the top item to enforce condition 2 (this can be done with numpy array operations without explicit for loops). Repeat using a loop for k in range(n_max) or something equivalent. This will enforce condition 3, and should be the only explicit for loop in your code.
  • Structure your code cleanly with helper functions for readability.

  • Use matplotlib.pyplot.plot to place a well-visible red dot at each selected pixel (no explicit for loops needed here).
